description:
## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
security
## Location
src/plugins/manager.rs:575-608
## Violation
The path-traversal guard canonicalises BOTH the marketplace dir and the per-plugin source, then checks starts_with. Between the check and the subsequent copy_dir_recursive, a symlink swap on `canonical_marketplace` itself (e.g., a malicious marketplace that just got pulled mutates one of its inner dirs into a symlink to /etc) bypasses the guard. Quoted lines:

    let canonical = full.canonicalize().map_err(|e| { ... })?;
    let canonical_marketplace = marketplace_dir.canonicalize().map_err(|e| { ... })?;
    if !canonical.starts_with(&canonical_marketplace) {
        return Err(PluginError::IoError(format!(
            "Plugin path traversal detected: ...",
        )));
    }
    canonical
    ...
    copy_dir_recursive(&source_path, &dest).map_err(...)?;

The window is small but not zero — and the same marketplace.json that just landed in via `git_pull` is the same source the canonicalisation reads from. A racy clone whose post-clone hooks mutate the layout can exploit this. Combined with finding #727 (symlink-following copy) it becomes a working primitive for arbitrary local read.
## Mandated refactor
Open `marketplace_dir` once with `File::open` (which gives a directory fd on Unix) and use openat-style relative ops (`openat`, `linkat`) so the directory cannot be swapped under you. On platforms without dirfd support, copy into a temp dir under `marketplace_dir/.tmp-<uuid>/` and rename — the kernel enforces the inode identity rather than a path-string check.
## Filed from QA review dispatch
